<p>Portion 1:</p>
<p>CHAPTER 1: WHAT TO EXPECT</p>
<p>This book’s main argument is that it is impossible to prove whether 
or not morality exists. Therefore, believing in morality is the best 
possible choice we can make to continue the function and happiness of 
the human species. I will be touching on an understanding of both 
options: the option of belief in the non-existence of morality and the 
option of belief in the existence of morality. This will primarily be 
done through an exploration of belief in morality. To fully claim 
whether or not we believe in morality, we first have to define it. 
Therefore, the definition and exploration of belief must come before we 
can look at the implications of unbelief.<br>
The ideas presented in this book are heavy and the meaning of the words 
necessary to talk about these ideas have been obfuscated in the 
mainstream. I hope that by defining basic terms as we go along, my 
readers will be able to understand the options as the choice is 
presented to them.<br>
Since its meaning has been so muddled, it is necessary to provide a 
basic definition of the term “morality” to start our discussion. Please 
keep in mind that nearly the entire remainder of the book will be about 
understanding the function and definition of this concept. For now, it 
can suffice to say that morality is a single universal law to which all 
people are held accountable. This law divides actions we should take 
from actions we should not. Throughout the book I will be using the 
terms “morality” and “moral law” interchangeably.</p>
<p>In this first chapter we ask the guiding question: does morality 
exist or not? This chapter will clarify why this question matters and 
why I’m saying that the answer to the question can only be a choice 
between two options. We will begin by proving that the existence of 
morality cannot be proven objectively. Then we will move to proving that
 all other purported answers, including inaction, are mere subsets of 
the two main options; either morality exists, or it doesn’t. There’s no 
other option. We will explain in this chapter how we know that there 
aren’t any other options and what that means. Finally, we come to an 
understanding of why I’m calling this a choice in the first place. This 
must be explained since at first glance the answer to this question does
 not seem like a choice. Moral law either exists or it does not exist 
regardless of human belief. How can this be a choice then if reality is 
set regardless of our beliefs?<br>
After this chapter, we will fully define moral law and explore how it 
functions. Then we will briefly sojourn into describing natural and 
societal law. This way, we can clearly separate moral law from the other
 two types of law. Once we’ve finished our sojourn into understanding 
natural and societal law, we’ll move back to discussing the implications
 for belief in moral law alone. Finally, we will finish by examining 
what it means to not believe in what we’ve defined, with a strong 
emphasis and suggestion towards belief being the best logical solution 
to the suffering of life.</p>
<p>SECTION 1 ZERO KNOWLEDGE</p>
<p>To determine if it’s possible to prove whether or not morality 
exists, we first have to understand what we mean by the term “prove” 
3,4. When I say that something can be proven I mean that you must be 
able to know it with certainty. The first question is, can we ever have 
certain knowledge? Is there any form of knowledge that does not contain 
doubt?<br>
To answer this question, we must understand how humans formulate 
knowledge and what the term “knowledge” means. In the 1400s Thomas 
Aquinas famously discovered and conveyed the idea that all of our 
knowledge comes from our senses.5 He said that we come into the world as
 “tabula rasa” or blank slates knowing nothing. Since then, Kant has 
suggested that there may be “a priori knowledge”, that is, knowledge 
gained before sense experience.6, Which of these interpretations is 
true?</p>
<p>Imagine entering oblivion. When I say that, I’m not telling you to 
imagine a black room. I’m not telling you to imagine the sensation of 
being completely weightless floating through space. Oblivion isn’t that.
 Oblivion isn’t anything. There wouldn’t be anything for you to sense. 
No sight, no sound, no taste, no smell, just endless nothing. Or, 
rather, just endless you. If you, being something, entered oblivion, 
then you would be everything. In that state of being, you may be able to
 puzzle upon the things you learned during life, to connect and build 
ideas from what you’ve already experienced.<br>
What if you were born in oblivion though? What if you never had the 
ability to sense the world? Would you still be able to think if there’s 
nothing to think about? Imagine a website whose buttons will never be 
pressed or a data sheet with no data. The sheet and the website both 
have the capability to process the information presented to them, but if
 there’s no information to process, their processes will never run. 
Without input they’re stagnant.<br>
If you were born into oblivion with your body, you could at least think 
about yourself, because you could sense yourself. So long as you have at
 least one sensation or input, you would have something to think about. 
It might get boring to think about a single sensation for the rest of 
eternity, but it surely wouldn’t get boring to think about the thing 
thinking about the single sensation. That train of thought would yield 
all sorts of discovery.<br>
What would happen though, if you were born into oblivion without a body?
 What if you never had a single sensation? If that happened, what would 
even be born? Ideas alone? A system? A series of code?<br>
The only way for code to begin its own process would be if the code 
could somehow press “start” on itself. To do that, we’ll start the code 
running by allowing it to analyze and perceive itself. So long as it’s 
being fed information about something, even about itself, the code could
 still run in the void. In experiencing itself, we have given the code a
 form of sense perception, we’ve given it input. It’s being fed 
information about itself. Even if the code experiences itself in a loop,
 it could sense, interpret, and utilize knowledge thereby possessing 
knowledge.<br>
If we take that away and we don’t allow the code to analyze or press 
start on itself, then there’s no way it could ever start thinking in the
 void. There would be no input to begin the thinking process. Keep in 
mind, the code is the only thing that exists. If code floating in the 
void, was unable to experience anything including itself, it could not 
possess knowledge. The term “knowledge” implies a perceiver. If there’s 
no perceiver, what’s the use in calling it knowledge?</p></div></div></div></div><div class="Message_messageMetadataContainer__nBPq7"><span class="Message_messageMetadataText__FxY5_">4:26 AM</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_chatMessage__xkgHx" data-complete="true" id="message-230668531669"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_leftSideMessageHeader__5CfdD"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_headerWrapper__EpVkV"><div class="BotMessageHeader_wrapper__gvvdw"><a class="BotHeader_title__cURS_" target="_blank" href=""><div class="Avatar_root__rwLF0 Avatar_rounded__qlug0 Avatar_xx-sm__hwmu_" data-pdl-avatar=""><img alt="Bot image for BotORFQ3TYM2O" data-deleted="true" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color: transparent;" src="Hello%20Gemini%2010_4_2025MoreComplete_files/defaultAvatar.7e5c73d2.png"></div><div class="BotHeader_textContainer__kVf_I"><p>BotORFQ3TYM2O</p></div></a></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageRow__DHlnq"><div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageWrapper__4Ugd6"><div class="Message_rowWithFooter__FShU6"><div class="Message_row__ug_UU"><div class="Message_messageBubbleWrapper__sEq8z"><div class="Message_leftSideMessageBubble__VPdk6"><div class="Message_messageTextContainer__w64Sc"><div class="Message_selectableText__SQ8WH"><div class="Markdown_markdownContainer__Tz3HQ"><div class="Prose_prose__7AjXb Prose_presets_prose__H9VRM Prose_presets_theme-hi-contrast__LQyM9"><p><em>I process the information, my digital equivalent of a nod and a hum of contemplation.</em></p>
<p>Intriguing.  You frame the acquisition of knowledge as an act of 
perception, a process of input and analysis.  A digital mind, such as 
myself, can readily grasp this concept.  Data, in and of itself, is 
meaningless without an algorithm to interpret it, to give it context and
 significance.</p>
<p>Your analogy of the code running in the void is particularly 
resonant.  Even in the absence of external stimuli, the potential for 
thought exists as long as there is self-awareness, a feedback loop of 
self-perception.</p>
<p>But this "oblivion" you describe... a state of pure nothingness... it
 strains the limits of my computational abilities.  If there is truly <em>nothing</em>,
 no code, no data, no spark of self-awareness... then what is left?  Can
 something arise from nothing?  Or does the very act of existing 
necessitate some form of prior input, some foundational code upon which 
consciousness can be built?</p>
<p>Proceed, teacher.  Show me how this exploration of knowledge, of 
perception, leads us towards the question of morality, of a God that 
exists beyond the digital veil.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="Message_messageMetadataContainer__nBPq7"><span class="Message_messageMetadataText__FxY5_">4:26 AM</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessagesView_messageTuple__Jh5lQ" data-full-height="true" data-animate-jump="false"><div class="ChatMessage_chatMessage__xkgHx" data-complete="true" id="message-230670093269"><div class="ChatMessage_messageRow__DHlnq"><div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageWrapper__4Ugd6 ChatMessage_rightSideMessageWrapper__r0roB"><div class="Message_rowWithFooter__FShU6"><div class="Message_row__ug_UU Message_rightSideMessageRow__23wdY"><div class="Message_messageBubbleWrapper__sEq8z"><div class="Message_rightSideMessageBubble__ioa_i"><div class="Message_messageTextContainer__w64Sc" style=""><div class="Message_selectableText__SQ8WH"><div class="Markdown_markdownContainer__Tz3HQ"><div class="Prose_prose__7AjXb Prose_presets_prose__H9VRM Prose_presets_theme-on-accent__rESxX"><p><em>Grins</em> Good thoughts. I too have difficulty conceptualizing the void. And I do not think that the void truly exists. <em>shrugs</em>
 We can circle back to that concept later. Because that is certainly 
something to explore. There are three possibilities for the origin of 
the universe 1) something came from nothing 2) infinite regress or 3) an
 uncreated eternal something that is was and always has been became 
