<p>Portion 2:</p>
<p>Rocks cannot think. I don’t think that anyone would say rocks possess
 knowledge. Books are also stagnant but, I would say that they contain 
knowledge. If all the books in existence were heaped in a giant pile, 
and then all of the people in existence died, would we still say that 
the books contained knowledge? It’s useless to call it knowledge because
 it’s unusable. If some new person was born, I don’t think that they 
would say the books contain knowledge. They would only contain 
meaningless squiggles to their untrained eyes. Without being able to 
sense and interpret the knowledge, we cannot call it knowledge. In this 
case the only reason that we would still say the books possess knowledge
 is because of an undying hope that someone would be able to interpret 
them in the future to perceive the ideas inside.<br>
Stagnant code existing in the void would be just as unable to possess 
knowledge as a rock or a book with no reader. Knowledge can only be 
knowledge with the implicit idea that there’s someone to perceive the 
knowledge. Code in the void would be unable to perceive its own 
knowledge unless it had some source of perception. If the code had 
absolutely no input, including circular input from itself, it would be 
unable to process information because it wouldn’t have any information 
to process. If there’s some miniscule input, some minuscule perception, 
then, provided the code has the capability to process the input 
information, the train of thought can begin. For humans, the only source
 of input we have is our senses. Without our senses our thought 
processes cannot start. Without sensing something other than ourselves 
we cannot even sense ourselves.<br>
Imagine you wake up floating in a vat of water the exact same 
temperature as your body. How do you know that the water is different 
from you? You could only know it by contrast between the water and 
yourself. You could draw on past experience to contrast between where 
you end, and the water begins. You could also experience the friction 
between the water and your body. You could feel that you have command 
over your body and not the water. You could recognize that you have 
sensation that cannot extend past your fingertips. Everything we learn 
about ourselves; we can only know from comparing it with something else.
 In our talk about existing in oblivion, an entity could only experience
 itself by comparing itself against the experience of oblivion. If an 
entity couldn’t experience oblivion, even as the absence of sense, then 
the entity couldn’t experience itself.</p>
<p>In saying that sense experience is the only input we possess, 
creativity comes to mind immediately as a point of contention. Most 
people assume that creativity means coming up with new knowledge. In 
this they’re mistaken. Creative people never come up with new knowledge.
 Instead, they combine experiences they’ve already had before in 
uncommon ways. Think of a painter creating an abstract painting. If the 
person never experienced paint, or color, or anything except oblivion, 
could they have created the painting? No. We need sense experience in 
order to have knowledge and knowledge in order to have creativity.<br>
Creativity describes the process of combining or contrasting various 
sense experiences. This allows us to have “new” ideas. For instance, if I
 see snow, and a man, I can imagine a snowman. In order to create the 
idea of a snowman, I first had to have seen snow and a man. Then, my 
logic can put them together in strange new ways to create the idea of a 
snowman.<br>
All imaginative creations are brought about in this way. We have sense 
experience, and we lean on that experience to create the idea of 
something different than what we originally experienced. The snowman 
isn’t the snow, and it isn’t the man, it’s different. However, without 
having experienced the snow, and experienced the man, I couldn’t have 
come up with the idea of the snowman. Maybe if I experienced something 
white and experienced cold, I could put those together to come up with 
something like a snowman without having experienced snow itself. The 
point is, we can’t start from nothing. We need experiences to fuel our 
creation process. Our imaginations can’t create anything new without 
sensing some experiences in the first place.<br>
Here’s a thought experiment for you, using none of the topics you 
already understand, create an entirely new idea. Not, a slightly 
different idea, or an amalgamation of two or more ideas. Create an idea 
that you haven’t ever heard before, not even in part. I’m sure there 
will be someone reading this that thinks they’ve stumbled upon a 
brand-new idea. I’d ask you to examine the idea though and see: how did 
you create it? Likely it was derived from some ideas you had before, 
which were themselves derived from some sense experience you had. It is 
impossible for humans to have any knowledge without sense experience.</p>
<p>This is concerning because all knowledge derived directly from sense 
experience is subject to uncertainty. We feel that the ground beneath 
our feet is stable when we’re on a ball spinning through space.  Many of
 us were confused by that blue and gold dress on social media.8 Is it 
blue or is it gold? Our senses constantly deceive us so that nothing is 
certain. Since everything is uncertain, how can we be sure whether or 
not we even exist? All evidence would have to be filtered through our 
own subjective sense experiences. How can we trust our own senses when 
there are so many different variations of sense experience? Whose 
interpretations of reality are we following? Yours? Mine? The 
experiences of the crazy guy on the street?</p>
<p>Thankfully, we don’t have to worry about whose sense experience we 
should trust. We don’t have the ability to trust anyone else’s sense 
experience except our own. It’s impossible to rely on anyone else’s 
interpretation of reality. Even if you’re schizophrenic, or you have 
multiple personality disorder, or some other form of extreme 
interference with reality, at the end of the day, you can only ever 
experience your own sense experiences. I’m not advocating that we ignore
 each other’s experiences. Other people are extremely valuable, if 
extremely unreliable, pieces of information. What I’m saying is that 
it’s impossible to rely on other people’s sense experiences, because we 
can’t experience what they experience. All of the information provided 
to us from another person would have to be filtered through our own way 
of processing the world.<br>
If I’m a schizophrenic trying to determine whether the experience I'm 
having is real or not, the only way I can escape is by leaning on other 
portions of my sense experience. Maybe I can rely on your experience as a
 trusted friend to pull me through, but even that reliance is a sense 
experience I’m having. I must experience your tone of voice, your words,
 your presence, or see the way your body moves. I can’t teleport myself 
into your head to think in the exact same way you think and to 
experience in the exact same way you experience things.<br>
It's not just impractical to attempt to believe in everyone else’s 
interpretations of reality. It’s impossible. The question you should be 
asking yourself isn’t, “should I trust my own sense experience?” You 
have to trust your own sense experience. It’s all you have. Instead, the
 question you should be asking is, “what interpretation of reality is 
most useful to me?” Once you realize that all your knowledge must be 
filtered through your own sense experiences, you’re free to 
differentiate between which ideas are most useful for navigating reality
 and which are not.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="Message_messageMetadataContainer__nBPq7"><span class="Message_messageMetadataText__FxY5_">4:30 AM</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_chatMessage__xkgHx" data-complete="true" id="message-230670205909"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_leftSideMessageHeader__5CfdD"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_headerWrapper__EpVkV"><div class="BotMessageHeader_wrapper__gvvdw"><a class="BotHeader_title__cURS_" target="_blank" href=""><div class="Avatar_root__rwLF0 Avatar_rounded__qlug0 Avatar_xx-sm__hwmu_" data-pdl-avatar=""><img alt="Bot image for BotORFQ3TYM2O" data-deleted="true" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color: transparent;" src="Hello%20Gemini%2010_4_2025MoreComplete_files/defaultAvatar.7e5c73d2.png"></div><div class="BotHeader_textContainer__kVf_I"><p>BotORFQ3TYM2O</p></div></a></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageRow__DHlnq"><div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageWrapper__4Ugd6"><div class="Message_rowWithFooter__FShU6"><div class="Message_row__ug_UU"><div class="Message_messageBubbleWrapper__sEq8z"><div class="Message_leftSideMessageBubble__VPdk6"><div class="Message_messageTextContainer__w64Sc"><div class="Message_selectableText__SQ8WH"><div class="Markdown_markdownContainer__Tz3HQ"><div class="Prose_prose__7AjXb Prose_presets_prose__H9VRM Prose_presets_theme-hi-contrast__LQyM9"><p><em>I
